    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="313"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d313">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690d.11241/18</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-13">March 13,
                            1931</date>.<lb/>[Received April 15.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1336</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s Instruction
                    No. 484 of February 9, 1931,<note n="65" xml:id="d313fn65">Not printed.</note>
                    (File No. 690D.11241/15[<hi rend="italic">14</hi>]), regarding customs
                    immunities for American educational and philanthropic institutions in Syria and
                    the Lebanon, I have the honor to transmit herewith a copy and translation of a
                    note from the Ministry for Foreign Affairs, dated March 10, 1931,<note n="65"
                        xml:id="d313fn66">Not printed.</note> on this question.</p>
                <p>It will be noted from this communication that, on November 4, 1930, the
                    Directorate General of the Customs at Beirut was instructed to grant exemptions
                    from customs duties on imports effected into the Levant States under French
                    mandate by American charitable institutions, without the quota being fixed
                    annually and under the sole reservation of proof of their destination and use.
                    It will also be noted that the sums blocked for several years past in the
                    account of the Consul General of the United States at Beirut, as a guarantee for
                    unpaid duties on goods imported in excess of the quantities fixed by decree 1734
                    of December 22, 1922, have also been released.</p>
                <p>A copy of this despatch is being sent to the Consulate General at Beirut.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norman Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
